@Node History "Program History"

 History
 =======

 1.0 - First release

 1.1 - The ARexx command CALL would return random result codes when it
       was successful.

     - Incomplete node numbers will now be completed using the default
       node. See configuration and usage for more details.

     - TrapDispatcher will now start without an configuration file
       and then use the default values.

     - TrapDispatcher caused Enforcerhits when there was an error
       in the configuration file.

     - New configuration keyword: "MaxFailed". If a call to a node
       has failed more times than allowed, the call will be removed
       from the list. This was added so that wrong passwords,
       unreliable modems etc can't give you a high phonebill...

     - You can now control the listview using the cursor keys.

     - Two new switches for the ARexx command "CALL" and for the
       command-line: REQ and FORCE

     - REQ is now used in the ScanPoll.rexx script. If an error
       occurs, a requester will appear.

     - New ARexx command: GETERROR. This gets the result of the last
       CALL command as a brief string describing the error. You can
       find the string in the "result" variable. Make sure that you
       have "options results" in your ARexx script.

     - Three new useful ARexx scripts are included: CallExist.rexx,
       Deliver.rexx and IntuiNode.rexx.

     - Support for Zone Mail Hour added. Now TrapDispatcher will only
       call non-CM nodes during ZMH. ZMH can be toggled either using
       ARexx or manually using the menus.

 1.2 - The scrolling arrows below the scrollbar didn't work before.

     - TrapDispatcher doesn't return 10 anymore when a command is passed
       on to an already running copy of TrapDispatcher.

     - Deliver.rexx has been updated. The old version of the ARexx script
       didn't know about unpacked netmail packets (#?.?ut). Thanks to Mario
       Bonelli for telling me about this...

     - TrapDispatcher now warns the user if he is trying to call a node
       that is listed as Hold in the nodelist. If the call was added via
       the ARexx port, TrapDispatcher will just refuse to call the node
       unless the command was given with the FORCE parameter.

     - Support for the Txx flag according to FSC-0062 has been added. This
       flag tells TrapDispatcher about the online times of a node. This
       flag together with the CM flag tells TrapDispatcher if it is possible
       to call a node at the current time. Don't forget to tell TrapDispatcher
       about your timezone using the TimeZone configuration variable.

@EndNode

@Node Future "Future plans"

 I am currently thinking of implementing the following features:

 o Support for nodes running multiple lines. That is quite a lot of work
   and I am not quite sure how many Amigas there are that run multiline...

 o Adding FrontDoor-like features like View outbound, Send files, Request
   files and configuration of passwords. Please write me and tell me what
   you think. Should those parts be separate programs or included in
   TrapDispatcher?

@endnode
